b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\r\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\r\n<workbook_page xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/"\r\n\txmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\r\n\txmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\r\n\txmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\r\n\txmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/" id="p6_empirical_formulas">\r\n\t<head>\r\n\t\t<title>Determination of Empirical Formulas</title>\r\n\t\t<objref idref="emp_formulas"/>\r\n\t</head>\r\n\t<body>\r\n\t\t<p id="a3ca4695de4c4f6689c8d9633401d508">As previously mentioned, the most common approach\r\n\t\t\tto determining a compound\xe2\x80\x99s chemical formula is to first measure the masses of its\r\n\t\t\tconstituent elements. However, we must keep in mind that chemical formulas represent the\r\n\t\t\trelative numbers, not masses, of atoms in the substance. Therefore, any experimentally\r\n\t\t\tderived data involving mass must be used to derive the corresponding numbers of atoms in\r\n\t\t\tthe compound. To accomplish this, we can use molar masses to convert the mass of each\r\n\t\t\telement to a number of moles. We then consider the moles of each element relative to\r\n\t\t\teach other, converting these numbers into a whole-number ratio that can be used to\r\n\t\t\tderive the empirical formula of the substance. Consider a sample of compound determined\r\n\t\t\tto contain 1.71 g C and 0.287 g H. The corresponding numbers of atoms (in moles)\r\n\t\t\tare:</p>\r\n\t\t<formula>$$\\require{cancel}\\begin{array}{l}1.71\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm g\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\tC}\\;\\times\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm C}{12.01\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm g\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\tC}}\\;=\\;0.142\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm C\\\\\\\\0.287\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm g\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\tH}\\;\\times\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm H}{1.008\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm g\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\tH}}\\;=\\;0.284\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm H\\end{array}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t<p id="bf856e60901849f488d21db9938717af"> Thus, we can accurately represent this compound\r\n\t\t\twith the formula C <sub>0.142</sub> H <sub>0.248</sub> . Of course, per accepted\r\n\t\t\tconvention, formulas contain whole-number subscripts, which can be achieved by dividing\r\n\t\t\teach mol amount by the smaller of the two. </p>\r\n\t\t<formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{Carbon}\\;=\\;\\frac{0.142}{0.142}\\;=\\;1\\\\\\mathrm{Hydrogen}\\;=\\;\\frac{0.284}{0.142}\\;=2\\end{array}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t<p id="a48ef9ad33544c35bb6935c914b4025f"> This gives us the whole number ratio of C:H\r\n\t\t\tatoms in the compound as 1:2 or CH<sub>2</sub>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t<p id="c66d2421c06e434b9b8a1a0d3a7f2cfc"> The empirical formula for this compound is thus CH<sub>2</sub>.\r\n\t\t\t\t This may or not be the compound\xe2\x80\x99s molecular formula as well; however,\r\n\t\t\twe would need additional information to make that determination (as discussed later in\r\n\t\t\tthis section). </p>\r\n\t\t<p id="e04f3ac4abfe44bea9a41e4959a51e75">The process for determining the formula for an\r\n\t\t\tempirical formula are summarized in the steps below.</p>\r\n\t\t<image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\r\n\t\t<dl>\r\n\t\t\t<dt>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="ae2c577e21d3d4db3933ab87816b1a215"><em>Determination of Empirical\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tFormula</em></p>\r\n\t\t\t</dt>\r\n\t\t\t<dd>\r\n\t\t\t\t<ol id="i30f41cbf75394cd6878dc840901d43d5">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ae5e54de53d7f40c499ee8a09e6c3f12d">Convert the given amount of each\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\telement into moles.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</li>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aae5d14372d4840a3a731bcc23e4c18e8">Divide each mole amount by the\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\tsmallest of the mole values.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</li>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="adf74e8ea327a457da7408106f39c0eb9">If step 2 does not produce whole\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\tnumbers (or very close to it), find a multiple of all of the values that\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\tproduces all whole numbers.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</li>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<li>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="afa307ea91d0140ef8e707c864aebe70b">Write the chemical formula based\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\ton the whole number ratio of atoms in the compound.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</li>\r\n\t\t\t\t</ol>\r\n\t\t\t</dd>\r\n\t\t</dl>\r\n\t\t<image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\r\n\t\t\r\n\t\t<example>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p id="f6609011ae9c44728e1604c5f63cf703">Consider as another example a sample of\r\n\t\t\t\tcompound determined to contain 5.31 g Cl and 8.40 g O. What is\r\n\t\t\t\tthe empirical formula for this compound?</p>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="b9f3f39725f7435a8de67737d50e18c4">Convert to moles.</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\frac{5.31\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tg\\;\\mathrm{Cl}}{35.45\\;{\\displaystyle\\frac{\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tg}{\\mathrm{mol}}}\\mathrm{Cl}}\\;=\\;0.1498\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Cl}\\\\\\\\\\frac{8.40\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tg\\;\\mathrm O}{16.00\\;{\\displaystyle\\frac{\\mathrm g}{\\mathrm{mol}}}\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tO}\\;=\\;0.525\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm O\\end{array}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="d68ad6b4f5b54e95a516dd708bb4fad1">Divide each mole value by the smallest of the\r\n\t\t\t\tvalues.</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula>\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{Cl}\\;\\;\\frac{0.1498\\;\\mathrm{mol}}{0.1498\\;\\mathrm{mol}}\\;=\\;1\\\\\\\\\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tO\\;\\;\\;\\frac{0.525\\;\\mathrm{mol}}{0.1498\\;\\mathrm{mol}}\\;\\approx3.5\\end{array}</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="ce9f548046784693b2ee7447e7023cd0">\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0Notice this step of the process in\r\n\t\t\t\tthis example did not yield a whole number ratio.</p>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="a386bb8d9bbe4040a583eeb9a2b2a7f7">Find a multiple of the values that yields a\r\n\t\t\t\twhole number ratio.</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{Cl}\\;\\;\\frac{0.1498\\;\\mathrm{mol}}{0.1498\\;\\mathrm{mol}}\\;=\\;1\\;\\;\\times\\;\\;2\\;=\\;2\\\\\\\\\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tO\\;\\;\\;\\frac{0.525\\;\\mathrm{mol}}{0.1498\\;\\mathrm{mol}}\\;\\approx3.5\\;\\times\\;2\\;=\\;7\\end{array}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="fa53e23bfebf4c75aebf9a6589942880">Multiplying both mole values by 2 yields the\r\n\t\t\t\twhole number ratio 2:7.</p>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="de25b26f2bd64813af2c76e8eb84fdd9">Write the chemical formula.</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula> Cl<sub>2</sub>O<sub>7</sub>\r\n\t\t\t</formula>\r\n\t\t</example>\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="empirical_lbd_1" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="empirical_lbd_2" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="empirical_digt_1" purpose="didigetthis"/>\r\n\t\t<section>\r\n\t\t\t<title>Deriving Empirical Formulas from Percent Composition</title>\r\n\t\t\t<body>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="a71c8d17544b41fea715f93ebfe74ea6">Finally, with regard to deriving empirical\r\n\t\t\t\t\tformulas, consider instances in which a compound\xe2\x80\x99s percent composition is\r\n\t\t\t\t\tavailable rather than the absolute masses of the compound\xe2\x80\x99s constituent\r\n\t\t\t\t\telements. In such cases, the percent composition can be used to calculate the\r\n\t\t\t\t\tmasses of elements present in any convenient mass of compound; these masses can\r\n\t\t\t\t\tthen be used to derive the empirical formula in the usual fashion.</p>\r\n\t\t\t</body>\r\n\t\t</section>\r\n\t\t<example>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p id="ecf5df0ad12047fc960c4fe05defe340">The bacterial fermentation of grain to produce\r\n\t\t\t\tethanol forms a gas with a percent composition of 27.29% C and 72.71% O. What is the\r\n\t\t\t\tempirical formula for this gas?</p>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="a94d364f5d354498a0910bc204521808">Since the scale for percentages is 100, it is\r\n\t\t\t\tmost convenient to calculate the mass of elements present in a sample weighing 100\r\n\t\t\t\tg. The calculation is \xe2\x80\x9cmost convenient\xe2\x80\x9d because, per the definition for percent\r\n\t\t\t\tcomposition, the mass of a given element in grams is numerically equivalent to the\r\n\t\t\t\telement\xe2\x80\x99s mass percentage. This numerical equivalence results from the definition of\r\n\t\t\t\tthe \xe2\x80\x9cpercentage\xe2\x80\x9d unit, whose name is derived from the Latin phrase per centum\r\n\t\t\t\tmeaning \xe2\x80\x9cby the hundred.\xe2\x80\x9d Considering this definition, the mass percentages provided\r\n\t\t\t\tmay be more conveniently expressed as fractions:</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}27.29\\;\\%\\mathrm C\\;=\\;\\frac{27.29\\;\\mathrm g\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tC}{100\\;\\mathrm g\\;\\mathrm{compound}}\\\\\\\\72.71\\;\\%\\mathrm O\\;=\\;\\frac{72.71\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tg\\;\\mathrm O}{100\\;\\mathrm g\\;\\mathrm{compound}}\\end{array}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="aea48a76eb0a4a1d853282260c2ac9a0">The molar amounts of carbon and hydrogen in a\r\n\t\t\t\t100\xe2\x88\x92g sample are calculated by dividing each element\xe2\x80\x99s mass by its molar mass:</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\frac{27.29\\;\\mathrm g\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tC}{12.01\\;{\\displaystyle\\frac{\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tg}{\\mathrm{mol}}}}\\;=\\;2.272\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm C\\\\\\\\\\frac{72.71\\;\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tg\\;\\mathrm O}{16.00\\;{\\displaystyle\\frac{\\mathrm\r\n\t\t\t\tg}{\\mathrm{mol}}}}\\;=\\;4.544\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm O\\end{array}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="b4cbb25956a9479b9791a80863cecfc9">Coefficients for the tentative empirical\r\n\t\t\t\tformula are derived by dividing each molar amount by the lesser of the two:</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{Carbon}:\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\frac{2.272\\;\\mathrm{mol}}{2.272\\;\\mathrm{mol}}\\;=\\;1\\\\\\\\\\mathrm{Oxygen}:\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\frac{4.544\\;\\mathrm{mol}}{2.272\\;\\mathrm{mol}}\\;=\\;2\\end{array}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="b921ae0a1c0d42b28d7d9b7d36987c81">Since the resulting ratio is one carbon to two\r\n\t\t\t\toxygen atoms, the empirical formula is:</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula> CO<sub>2</sub>\r\n\t\t\t</formula>\r\n\t\t</example>\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="empirical_digt_2" purpose="didigetthis"/>\r\n\t\t<p id="fcda45a59ae94beda4ab29969c3d8bf6"> Adapted from <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface" target="new"\r\n\t\t\t\tinternal="false">Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" target="new" internal="false"\r\n\t\t\t\t>Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 License.</link>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t<p id="cffd841f94b344e18880b8b5609ad7ad"> Download for free at <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\r\n\t\t\t\ttarget="new" internal="false"\r\n\t\t\t\t>http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t</body>\r\n</workbook_page>\r\n'